  "prompt": "Complete an orbital diagram for scandium (Sc).?",
  "response": "To create an orbital diagram for scandium (Sc), we need to follow these steps:\n\n1. **Determine the atomic number and electron configuration:**\n   Scandium has an atomic number of 21, meaning it has 21 electrons. The electron configuration for scandium is:\n   \\[\n   1s^2 \\, 2s^2 \\, 2p^6 \\, 3s^2 \\, 3p^6 \\, 4s^2 \\, 3d^1\n   \\]\n\n2. **Draw the orbital diagram:**\n   An orbital diagram shows each orbital as a box and each electron as an arrow. The arrows are drawn with their spin direction (up or down). According to Hund's rule, electrons fill orbitals of the same energy level singly before pairing up.\n\nHere is the completed orbital diagram for scandium:\n\n```\n1s  \u2191\u2193\n2s  \u2191\u2193\n2p  \u2191\u2193  \u2191\u2193  \u2191\u2193\n3s  \u2191\u2193\n3p  \u2191\u2193  \u2191\u2193  \u2191\u2193\n4s  \u2191\u2193\n3d  \u2191    -    -    -    -\n```\n\nExplanation:\n- The 1s, 2s, 3s, and 4s orbitals each contain 2 electrons (one up arrow and one down arrow).\n- The 2p and 3p orbitals each contain 6 electrons, with 2 electrons in each of the three p orbitals.\n- The 3d orbitals start filling with one electron in the first 3d orbital.\n\nThis diagram accurately represents the electron configuration of scandium.",
